            "author_association": "COLLABORATOR",
            "body": "This is a general issue that applies for all C++ objects - they must be default initialized at the start of their scope and (usually) there isn't any way to catch any exception from the default constructor. In the specific case of class constructors it probably would be possible to guard the call to the default constructor, but in functions (for example) it really isn't.\r\n\r\nThe new `cpp_locals` directive avoids the need to default initialize so would help with this.",
